# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: extremal-combinatorics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] In mathematics, in the areas of order theory and combinatorics, **Dilworth's theorem** states that, in any finite partially ordered set, the maximum size of an antichain of incomparable elements equals the minimum number of chains needed to cover all elements.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] This number is called the **width** of the partial order.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] The theorem is named for the mathematician Robert P.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] A version of the theorem for infinite partially ordered sets states that, when there exists a decomposition into finitely many chains, or when there exists a finite upper bound on the size of an antichain, the sizes of the largest antichain and of the smallest chain decomposition are again equal.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] An antichain in a partially ordered set is a set of elements no two of which are comparable to each other, and a chain is a set of elements every two of which are comparable.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] A chain decomposition is a partition of the elements of the order into disjoint chains.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] Dilworth's theorem states that, in any finite partially ordered set, the largest antichain has the same size as the smallest chain decomposition.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] Here, the size of the antichain is its number of elements, and the size of the chain decomposition is its number of chains.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] The width of the partial order is defined as the common size of the antichain and chain decomposition.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] The following proof by induction on the size of the partially ordered set P is based on that of Galvin (1994).
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] Let P be a finite partially ordered set.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] The theorem holds trivially if P is empty.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] So, assume that P has at least one element, and let a be a maximal element of P .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] By induction, we assume that for some integer k the partially ordered set $P':=P\setminus \{a\}$ can be covered by k disjoint chains $C_{1},\dots ,C_{k}$ and has at least one antichain $A_{0}$ of size k .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] Let $A_{i}$ be an antichain of size k that contains $x_{i}$ .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] Fix arbitrary distinct indices i and j .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] Then $y\leq x_{j}$ , by the definition of $x_{j}$ .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] This implies that $x_{i}\not \geq x_{j}$ , since $x_{i}\not \geq y$ .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] By interchanging the roles of i and j in this argument we also have $x_{j}\not \geq x_{i}$ .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] Then by the choice of $x_{i}$ , $P\setminus K$ does not have an antichain of size k .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] Induction then implies that $P\setminus K$ can be covered by $k-1$ disjoint chains since $A\setminus \{x_{i}\}$ is an antichain of size $k-1$ in $P\setminus K$ .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] Thus, P can be covered by k disjoint chains, as required.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] Next, if $a\not \geq x_{i}$ for each $i\in \{1,2,\dots ,k\}$ , then $A\cup \{a\}$ is an antichain of size $k+1$ in P (since a is maximal in P ).
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] Like a number of other results in combinatorics, Dilworth's theorem is equivalent to Kőnig's theorem on bipartite graph matching and several other related theorems including Hall's marriage theorem.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] To prove Dilworth's theorem for a partial order *S* with *n* elements, using Kőnig's theorem, define a bipartite graph *G* = (*U*,*V*,*E*) where *U* = *V* = *S* and where (*u*,*v*) is an edge in *G* when *u* < *v* in *S*.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] By Kőnig's theorem, there exists a matching *M* in *G*, and a set of vertices *C* in *G*, such that each edge in the graph contains at least one vertex in *C* and such that *M* and *C* have the same cardinality *m*.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] Let *A* be the set of elements of *S* that do not correspond to any vertex in *C*; then *A* has at least *n* - *m* elements (possibly more if *C* contains vertices corresponding to the same element on both sides of the bipartition) and no two elements of *A* are comparable to each other.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] Let *P* be a family of chains formed by including *x* and *y* in the same chain whenever there is an edge (*x*,*y*) in *M*; then *P* has *n* - *m* chains.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] Therefore, we have constructed an antichain and a partition into chains with the same cardinality.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] To prove Kőnig's theorem from Dilworth's theorem, for a bipartite graph *G* = (*U*,*V*,*E*), form a partial order on the vertices of *G* in which *u* < *v* exactly when *u* is in *U*, *v* is in *V*, and there exists an edge in *E* from *u* to *v*.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] By Dilworth's theorem, there exists an antichain *A* and a partition into chains *P* both of which have the same size.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] But the only nontrivial chains in the partial order are pairs of elements corresponding to the edges in the graph, so the nontrivial chains in *P* form a matching in the graph.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] The complement of *A* forms a vertex cover in *G* with the same cardinality as this matching.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] This connection to bipartite matching allows the width of any partial order to be computed in polynomial time.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] More precisely, *n*-element partial orders of width *k* can be recognized in time *O*(*kn*2).
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] Dilworth's theorem for infinite partially ordered sets states that a partially ordered set has finite width *w* if and only if it may be partitioned into *w* chains.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] For, suppose that an infinite partial order *P* has width *w*, meaning that there are at most a finite number *w* of elements in any antichain.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] By the assumption that *P* has width *w*, and by the finite version of Dilworth's theorem, every finite subset *S* of *P* has a *w*-colorable incomparability graph.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] Therefore, by the De Bruijn–Erdős theorem, *P* itself also has a *w*-colorable incomparability graph, and thus has the desired partition into chains.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] However, the theorem does not extend so simply to partially ordered sets in which the width, and not just the cardinality of the set, is infinite.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] In this case the size of the largest antichain and the minimum number of chains needed to cover the partial order may be very different from each other.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] In particular, for every infinite cardinal number κ there is an infinite partially ordered set of width ℵ0 whose partition into the fewest chains has κ chains.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] Perles (1963) discusses analogues of Dilworth's theorem in the infinite setting.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] A dual of Dilworth's theorem states that the size of the largest chain in a partial order (if finite) equals the smallest number of antichains into which the order may be partitioned.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] Its proof is much simpler than the proof of Dilworth's theorem itself: for any element *x*, consider the chains that have *x* as their largest element, and let *N*(*x*) denote the size of the largest of these *x*-maximal chains.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] Then each set *N*−1(*i*), consisting of elements that have equal values of *N*, is an antichain, and these antichains partition the partial order into a number of antichains equal to the size of the largest chain.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] A comparability graph is an undirected graph formed from a partial order by creating a vertex per element of the order, and an edge connecting any two comparable elements.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] Thus, a clique in a comparability graph corresponds to a chain, and an independent set in a comparability graph corresponds to an antichain.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] Any induced subgraph of a comparability graph is itself a comparability graph, formed from the restriction of the partial order to a subset of its elements.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] An undirected graph is perfect if, in every induced subgraph, the chromatic number equals the size of the largest clique.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] Every comparability graph is perfect: this is essentially just Mirsky's theorem, restated in graph-theoretic terms.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] By the perfect graph theorem of Lovász (1972), the complement of any perfect graph is also perfect.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] Therefore, the complement of any comparability graph is perfect; this is essentially just Dilworth's theorem itself, restated in graph-theoretic terms (Berge & Chvátal 1984).
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] Thus, the complementation property of perfect graphs can provide an alternative proof of Dilworth's theorem.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] The Boolean lattice *B**n* is the power set of an *n*-element set *X*—essentially {1, 2, …, *n*}—ordered by inclusion or, notationally, (2[*n*], ⊆).
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] In other words, a largest family of incomparable subsets of *X* is obtained by selecting the subsets of *X* that have median size.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] The Lubell–Yamamoto–Meshalkin inequality also concerns antichains in a power set and can be used to prove Sperner's theorem.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] If we order the integers in the interval [1, 2*n*] by divisibility, the subinterval [*n* + 1, 2*n*] forms an antichain with cardinality *n*.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] A partition of this partial order into *n* chains is easy to achieve: for each odd integer *m* in [1,2*n*], form a chain of the numbers of the form *m*2*i*.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] Therefore, by Dilworth's theorem, the width of this partial order is *n*.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] The Erdős–Szekeres theorem on monotone subsequences can be interpreted as an application of Dilworth's theorem to partial orders of order dimension two.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/dilworth-s-theorem] The "convex dimension" of an antimatroid is defined as the minimum number of chains needed to define the antimatroid, and Dilworth's theorem can be used to show that it equals the width of an associated partial order; this connection leads to a polynomial time algorithm for convex dimension.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] In mathematics, the **Erdős–Ko–Rado theorem** limits the number of sets in a family of sets for which every two sets have at least one element in common.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] Paul Erdős, Chao Ko, and Richard Rado proved the theorem in 1938, but did not publish it until 1961.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] It is part of the field of combinatorics, and one of the central results of extremal set theory.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] The theorem applies to families of sets that all have the same size, r , and are all subsets of some larger set of size n .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] One way to construct a family of sets with these parameters, each two sharing an element, is to choose a single element to belong to all the subsets, and then form all of the subsets of size r that contain the chosen element.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] The Erdős–Ko–Rado theorem states that when n is large enough for the problem to be nontrivial ( $n\geq 2r$ ) this construction produces the largest possible intersecting families.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] When $n=2r$ there are other equally-large families, but for larger values of n only the families constructed in this way can be largest.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] The Erdős–Ko–Rado theorem can also be described in terms of hypergraphs or independent sets in Kneser graphs.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] Several analogous theorems apply to other kinds of mathematical object than sets, including linear subspaces, permutations, and strings.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] They again describe the largest possible intersecting families as being formed by choosing an element and forming the family of all objects that contain the chosen element.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] Suppose that ${\mathcal {A}}$ is a family of distinct r -element subsets of an n -element set with $n\geq 2r$ , and that each two subsets share at least one element.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] The same result can be formulated as part of the theory of hypergraphs.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] A family of sets may also be called a hypergraph, and when all the sets (which are called "hyperedges" in this context) are the same size r , it is called an r -uniform hypergraph.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] The theorem thus gives an upper bound for the number of pairwise overlapping hyperedges in an r -uniform hypergraph with n vertices and $n\geq 2r$ .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] An independent set is a collection of vertices that has no edges between its pairs, and the independence number is the size of the largest independent set.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] Paul Erdős, Chao Ko, and Richard Rado proved this theorem in 1938 after working together on it in England.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] Rado had moved from Berlin to the University of Cambridge and Erdős from Hungary to the University of Manchester, both escaping the influence of Nazi Germany; Ko was a student of Louis J.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] However, they did not publish the result until 1961, with the long delay occurring in part because of a lack of interest in combinatorial set theory in the 1930s, and increased interest in the topic in the 1960s.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] The 1961 paper stated the result in an apparently more general form, in which the subsets were only required to be size *at most* r , and to satisfy the additional requirement that no subset be contained in any other.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] A family of subsets meeting these conditions can be enlarged to subsets of size exactly r either by an application of Hall's marriage theorem, or by choosing each enlarged subset from the same chain in a symmetric chain decomposition of sets.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] A simple way to construct an intersecting family of r -element sets whose size exactly matches the Erdős–Ko–Rado bound is to choose any fixed element x , and let ${\mathcal {A}}$ consist of all r -element subsets that include x .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] Any two sets in this family intersect, because they both include 1 .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] The number of sets is ${\tbinom {n-1}{r-1}}$ , because after the fixed element is chosen there remain $n-1$ other elements to choose, and each set chooses $r-1$ of these remaining elements.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] When $n>2r$ this is the only intersecting family of this size.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] However, when $n=2r$ , there is a more general construction.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] Each r -element set can be matched up to its complement, the only r -element set from which it is disjoint.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] Then, choose one set from each of these complementary pairs.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] where every two sets intersect despite no element belonging to all three sets.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] In this example, all of the sets have been complemented from the ones in the first example, but it is also possible to complement only some of the sets.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] When $n>2r$ , families of the first type (variously known as stars, dictatorships, juntas, centered families, or principal families) are the unique maximum families.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] In this case, a family of nearly-maximum size has an element which is common to almost all of its sets.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] This property has been called *stability*, although the same term has also been used for a different property, the fact that (for a wide range of parameters) deleting randomly-chosen edges from the Kneser graph does not increase the size of its independent sets.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] An intersecting family of r -element sets may be maximal, in that no further set can be added (even by extending the ground set) without destroying the intersection property, but not of maximum size.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] An example with $n=7$ and $r=3$ is the set of seven lines of the Fano plane, much less than the Erdős–Ko–Rado bound of 15.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] More generally, the lines of any finite projective plane of order q form a maximal intersecting family that includes only n sets, for the parameters $r=q+1$ and $n=q^{2}+q+1$ .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] The Fano plane is the case $q=2$ of this construction.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] The smallest possible size of a maximal intersecting family of r -element sets, in terms of r , is unknown but at least $3r$ for $r\geq 4$ .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] Projective planes produce maximal intersecting families whose number of sets is $r^{2}-r+1$ , but for infinitely many choices of r there exist smaller maximal intersecting families of size ${\tfrac {3}{4}}r^{2}$ .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] This result is called the **Hilton–Milner theorem**, after its proof by Anthony Hilton and Eric Charles Milner in 1967.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] The original proof of the Erdős–Ko–Rado theorem used induction on n .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] The base case, for $n=2r$ , follows easily from the facts that an intersecting family cannot include both a set and its complement, and that in this case the bound of the Erdős–Ko–Rado theorem is exactly half the number of all r -element sets.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] The induction step for larger n uses a method called *shifting*, of substituting elements in intersecting families to make the family smaller in lexicographic order and reduce it to a canonical form that is easier to analyze.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] Katona gave the following short proof using double counting.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] However, only some of these intervals can belong to ${\mathcal {A}}$ , because they do not all intersect.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] Katona's key observation is that at most r intervals from a single cyclic order may belong to ${\mathcal {A}}$ .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] This is because, if $(a_{1},a_{2},\dots ,a_{r})$ is one of these intervals, then every other interval of the same cyclic order that belongs to ${\mathcal {A}}$ separates $a_{i}$ from $a_{i+1}$ , for some i , by containing precisely one of these two elements.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] The two intervals that separate these elements are disjoint, so at most one of them can belong to ${\mathcal {A}}$ .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] Thus, the number of intervals in ${\mathcal {A}}$ is at most one plus the number $r-1$ of pairs that can be separated.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] Based on this idea, it is possible to count the pairs $(S,C)$ , where S is a set in ${\mathcal {A}}$ and C is a cyclic order for which S is an interval, in two ways.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] First, for each set S one may generate C by choosing one of $r!$ permutations of S and $(n-r)!$ permutations of the remaining elements, showing that the number of pairs is $|{\mathcal {A}}|r!(n-r)!$ .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] And second, there are $(n-1)!$ cyclic orders, each of which has at most r intervals of ${\mathcal {A}}$ , so the number of pairs is at most $r(n-1)!$ .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] It is also possible to derive the Erdős–Ko–Rado theorem as a special case of the Kruskal–Katona theorem, another important result in extremal set theory.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] A generalization of the theorem applies to subsets that are required to have large intersections.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] This version of the theorem has three parameters: n , the number of elements the subsets are drawn from, r , the size of the subsets, as before, and t , the minimum size of the intersection of any two subsets.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] For the original form of the Erdős–Ko–Rado theorem, $t=1$ .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] In general, for n large enough with respect to the other two parameters, the generalized theorem states that the size of a t -intersecting family of subsets is at most ${\binom {n-t}{r-t}}.$ More precisely, this bound holds when $n\geq (t+1)(r-t+1)$ , and does not hold for smaller values of n .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] When $n>(t+1)(r-t+1)$ , the only t -intersecting families of this size are obtained by designating t elements as the common intersection of all the subsets, and constructing the family of all r -element subsets that include these t designated elements.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] The maximal size of a t-intersecting family when $n<(t+1)(r-t+1)$ was determined by Ahlswede and Khachatrian, in their Ahlswede–Khachatrian theorem.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] The corresponding graph-theoretic formulation of this generalization involves Johnson graphs in place of Kneser graphs.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] The theorem can also be generalized to families in which every h subsets have a common intersection.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] Because this strengthens the condition that every pair intersects (for which $h=2$ ), these families have the same bound on their maximum size, ${\tbinom {n-1}{r-1}}$ when n is sufficiently large.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] However, in this case the meaning of "sufficiently large" can be relaxed from $n\geq 2r$ to $n\geq {\tfrac {h}{h-1}}r$ .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] Many results analogous to the Erdős–Ko–Rado theorem, but for other classes of objects than finite sets, are known.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] These generally involve a statement that the largest families of intersecting objects, for some definition of intersection, are obtained by choosing an element and constructing the family of all objects that include that chosen element.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] There is a q-analog of the Erdős–Ko–Rado theorem for intersecting families of linear subspaces over finite fields.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] In this case, a largest intersecting family of subspaces may be obtained by choosing any nonzero vector and constructing the family of subspaces of the given dimension that all contain the chosen vector.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] Two permutations on the same set of elements are defined to be intersecting if there is some element that has the same image under both permutations.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] On an n -element set, there is an obvious family of $(n-1)!$ intersecting permutations, the permutations that fix one of the elements (the stabilizer subgroup of this element).
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] The analogous theorem is that no intersecting family of permutations can be larger, and that the only intersecting families of size $(n-1)!$ are the cosets of one-element stabilizers.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] These can be described more directly as the families of permutations that map some fixed element to another fixed element.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] More generally, for any t and sufficiently large n , a family of permutations each pair of which has t elements in common has maximum size $(n-t)!$ , and the only families of this size are cosets of pointwise stabilizers.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] Another analog of the theorem, for partitions of a set, includes as a special case the perfect matchings of a complete graph $K_{n}$ (with n even).
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] There are $(n-1)!!$ matchings, where ${\displaystyle$ denotes the double factorial.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] The largest family of matchings that pairwise intersect (meaning that they have an edge in common) has size $(n-3)!!$ and is obtained by fixing one edge and choosing all ways of matching the remaining $n-2$ vertices.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] A partial geometry is a system of finitely many abstract points and lines, satisfying certain axioms including the requirement that all lines contain the same number of points and all points belong to the same number of lines.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] In a partial geometry, a largest system of pairwise-intersecting lines can be obtained from the set of lines through any single point.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] A signed set consists of a set together with sign function that maps each element to $\{1,-1\}$ .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] Two signed sets may be said to intersect when they have a common element that has the same sign in each of them.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] Then an intersecting family of r -element signed sets, drawn from an n -element universe, consists of at most $2^{r-1}{\binom {n-1}{r-1}}$ signed sets.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] This number of signed sets may be obtained by fixing one element and its sign and letting the remaining $r-1$ elements and signs vary.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] For strings of length n over an alphabet of size q , two strings can be defined to intersect if they have a position where both share the same symbol.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] The largest intersecting families are obtained by choosing one position and a fixed symbol for that position, and letting the rest of the positions vary arbitrarily.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] These families consist of ${\textstyle q^{n-1}}$ strings, and are the only pairwise intersecting families of this size.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] These results can be interpreted graph-theoretically in terms of the Hamming scheme.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] Is the largest family of intersecting triangulations of a convex polygon obtained by cutting off one vertex and choosing all triangulations of the remaining polygon?
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] An unproven conjecture, posed by Gil Kalai and Karen Meagher, concerns another analog for the family of triangulations of a convex polygon with n vertices.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] The number of all triangulations is a Catalan number $C_{n-2}$ , and the conjecture states that a family of triangulations every pair of which shares an edge has maximum size $C_{n-3}$ .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] An intersecting family of size exactly $C_{n-3}$ may be obtained by cutting off a single vertex of the polygon by a triangle, and choosing all ways of triangulating the remaining $(n-1)$ -vertex polygon.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] The Erdős–Ko–Rado theorem can be used to prove the following result in probability theory.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] Let $x_{i}$ be independent 0–1 random variables with probability $p\geq {\tfrac {1}{2}}$ of being one, and let $c({\vec {x}})$ be any fixed convex combination of these variables.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] Then $\Pr \left[c({\vec {x}})\geq {\tfrac {1}{2}}\right]\geq p.$ The proof involves observing that subsets of variables whose indicator vectors have large convex combinations must be non-disjoint and using the Erdős–Ko–Rado theorem to bound the number of these subsets.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] The stability properties of the Erdős–Ko–Rado theorem play a key role in an efficient algorithm for finding monochromatic edges in improper colorings of Kneser graphs.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/erdős-ko-rado-theorem] The Erdős–Ko–Rado theorem has also been used to characterize the symmetries of the space of phylogenetic trees.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/extremal-combinatorics] Much of extremal combinatorics concerns classes of sets; this is called **extremal set theory**.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/extremal-combinatorics] For instance, in an *n*-element set, what is the largest number of *k*-element subsets that can pairwise intersect one another?
[src:extremal-combinatorics/extremal-combinatorics] What is the largest number of subsets of which none contains any other?
[src:extremal-combinatorics/extremal-combinatorics] The latter question is answered by Sperner's theorem, which gave rise to much of extremal set theory.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/extremal-combinatorics] Another kind of example: How many people can be invited to a party where among each three people there are two who know each other and two who don't know each other?
[src:extremal-combinatorics/extremal-combinatorics] Ramsey theory shows that at most five persons can attend such a party (see Theorem on Friends and Strangers).
[src:extremal-combinatorics/extremal-combinatorics] Or, suppose we are given a finite set of nonzero integers, and are asked to mark as large a subset as possible of this set under the restriction that the sum of any two marked integers cannot be marked.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/extremal-combinatorics] It appears that (independent of what the given integers actually are) we can always mark at least one-third of them.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/probabilistic-method] In mathematics, the **probabilistic method** is a nonconstructive method, primarily used in combinatorics and pioneered by Paul Erdős, for proving the existence of a prescribed kind of mathematical object.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/probabilistic-method] It works by showing that if one randomly chooses objects from a specified class, the probability that the result is of the prescribed kind is strictly greater than zero.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/probabilistic-method] Although the proof uses probability, the final conclusion is determined for certain, without any possible error.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/probabilistic-method] This method has now been applied to other areas of mathematics such as number theory, linear algebra, and real analysis, as well as in computer science (e.g. randomized rounding) and information theory.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/probabilistic-method] If every object in a collection of objects fails to have a certain property, then the probability that a random object chosen from the collection has that property is zero.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/probabilistic-method] Thus, by contraposition, if the probability that a random object chosen from the collection has that property is nonzero, then some object in the collection must possess the property.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/probabilistic-method] Similarly, showing that the probability is (strictly) less than 1 can be used to prove the existence of an object that does *not* satisfy the prescribed properties.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/probabilistic-method] Another way to use the probabilistic method is by calculating the expected value of some random variable.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/probabilistic-method] If it can be shown that the random variable can take on a value less than the expected value, this proves that the random variable can also take on some value greater than the expected value.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/probabilistic-method] Common tools used in the probabilistic method include Markov's inequality, the Chernoff bound, and the Lovász local lemma.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/probabilistic-method] Although others before him proved theorems via the probabilistic method (for example, Szele's 1943 result that there exist tournaments containing a large number of Hamiltonian cycles), many of the most well known proofs using this method are due to Erdős.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/probabilistic-method] The first example below describes one such result from 1947 that gives a proof of a lower bound for the Ramsey number $R(r,r)$ .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/probabilistic-method] Suppose we have a complete graph on n vertices.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/probabilistic-method] We wish to show (for small enough values of n ) that it is possible to color the edges of the graph in two colors (say red and blue) so that there is no complete subgraph on r vertices which is monochromatic (every edge colored the same color).
[src:extremal-combinatorics/probabilistic-method] Color each edge independently with probability $1/2$ of being red and $1/2$ of being blue.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/probabilistic-method] For any set $S_{r}$ of r vertices from our graph, define the variable $X(S_{r})$ to be 1 if every edge amongst the r vertices is the same color, and 0 otherwise.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/probabilistic-method] Note that the number of monochromatic r -subgraphs is the sum of $X(S_{r})$ over all possible subsets $S_{r}$ .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/probabilistic-method] (the factor of 2 comes because there are two possible colors).
[src:extremal-combinatorics/probabilistic-method] This holds true for any of the $C(n,r)$ possible subsets we could have chosen, i.e. i ranges from 1 to $C(n,r)$ .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/probabilistic-method] Consider what happens if this value is less than 1 .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/probabilistic-method] Since the expected number of monochromatic r -subgraphs is strictly less than 1 , there exists a coloring satisfying the condition that the number of monochromatic r -subgraphs is strictly less than 1 .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/probabilistic-method] The number of monochromatic r -subgraphs in this random coloring is a non-negative integer, hence it must be 0 ( 0 is the only non-negative integer less than 1 ).
[src:extremal-combinatorics/probabilistic-method] (which holds, for example, for $n=5$ and $r=4$ ), there must exist a coloring in which there are no monochromatic r -subgraphs.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/probabilistic-method] By definition of the Ramsey number, this implies that $R(r,r)$ must be bigger than n .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/probabilistic-method] In particular, $R(r,r)$ must grow at least exponentially with r .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/probabilistic-method] A weakness of this argument is that it is entirely nonconstructive.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/probabilistic-method] The problem of finding such a coloring has been open for more than 50 years.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/probabilistic-method] A 1959 paper of Erdős (see reference cited below) addressed the following problem in graph theory: given positive integers g and k, does there exist a graph G containing only cycles of length at least g, such that the chromatic number of G is at least k?
[src:extremal-combinatorics/probabilistic-method] It can be shown that such a graph exists for any g and k, and the proof is reasonably simple.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/probabilistic-method] Let n be very large and consider a random graph G on n vertices, where every edge in G exists with probability *p* = *n*1/*g*−1.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/probabilistic-method] and each of them is present in G with probability *pi*.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/probabilistic-method] For sufficiently large n, the probability that a graph from the distribution has both properties is positive, as the events for these properties cannot be disjoint (if they were, their probabilities would sum up to more than 1).
[src:extremal-combinatorics/probabilistic-method] Here comes the trick: since G has these two properties, we can remove at most *n*/2 vertices from G to obtain a new graph *G′* on $n'\geq n/2$ vertices that contains only cycles of length at least g.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/probabilistic-method] We can see that this new graph has no independent set of size $\left\lceil {\frac {n'}{k}}\right\rceil$ .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/probabilistic-method] *G′* can only be partitioned into at least k independent sets, and, hence, has chromatic number at least k.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/probabilistic-method] This result gives a hint as to why the computation of the chromatic number of a graph is so difficult: even when there are no local reasons (such as small cycles) for a graph to require many colors the chromatic number can still be arbitrarily large.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/sperner-s-theorem] This result is sometimes called Sperner's lemma, but the name "Sperner's lemma" also refers to an unrelated result on coloring triangulations.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/sperner-s-theorem] To differentiate the two results, the result on the size of a Sperner family is now more commonly known as Sperner's theorem.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/sperner-s-theorem] A family of sets in which none of the sets is a strict subset of another is called a Sperner family, or an antichain of sets, or a clutter.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/sperner-s-theorem] For example, the family of *k*-element subsets of an *n*-element set is a Sperner family.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/sperner-s-theorem] No set in this family can contain any of the others, because a containing set has to be strictly bigger than the set it contains, and in this family all sets have equal size.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/sperner-s-theorem] The value of *k* that makes this example have as many sets as possible is *n*/2 if *n* is even, or either of the nearest integers to *n*/2 if *n* is odd.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/sperner-s-theorem] For this choice, the number of sets in the family is ${\tbinom {n}{\lfloor n/2\rfloor }}$ .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/sperner-s-theorem] Sperner's theorem states that these examples are the largest possible Sperner families over an *n*-element set.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/sperner-s-theorem] 2. equality holds if and only if *S* consists of all subsets of an *n*-element set that have size $\lfloor n/2\rfloor$ or all that have size $\lceil n/2\rceil$ .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/sperner-s-theorem] Sperner's theorem can also be stated in terms of partial order width.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/sperner-s-theorem] The family of all subsets of an *n*-element set (its power set) can be partially ordered by set inclusion; in this partial order, two distinct elements are said to be incomparable when neither of them contains the other.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/sperner-s-theorem] The width of a partial order is the largest number of elements in an antichain, a set of pairwise incomparable elements.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/sperner-s-theorem] Translating this terminology into the language of sets, an antichain is just a Sperner family, and the width of the partial order is the maximum number of sets in a Sperner family.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/sperner-s-theorem] Thus, another way of stating Sperner's theorem is that the width of the inclusion order on a power set is ${\binom {n}{\lfloor n/2\rfloor }}$ .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/sperner-s-theorem] A graded partially ordered set is said to have the Sperner property when one of its largest antichains is formed by a set of elements that all have the same rank.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/sperner-s-theorem] In this terminology, Sperner's theorem states that the partially ordered set of all subsets of a finite set, partially ordered by set inclusion, has the Sperner property.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/sperner-s-theorem] There are many proofs of Sperner's theorem, each leading to different generalizations (see Anderson (1987)).
[src:extremal-combinatorics/sperner-s-theorem] The following proof is due to Lubell (1966).
[src:extremal-combinatorics/sperner-s-theorem] Let *sk* denote the number of *k*-sets in *S*.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/sperner-s-theorem] To have equality, all the inequalities in the preceding proof must be equalities.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/sperner-s-theorem] if and only if $k=\lfloor {n/2}\rfloor$ or $\lceil {n/2}\rceil ,$ we conclude that equality implies that *S* consists only of sets of sizes $\lfloor {n/2}\rfloor$ or $\lceil {n/2}\rceil .$ For even *n* that concludes the proof of part 2.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/sperner-s-theorem] For odd *n* there is more work to do, which we omit here because it is complicated.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/sperner-s-theorem] There are several generalizations of Sperner's theorem for subsets of ${\mathcal {P}}(E),$ the poset of all subsets of *E*.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/sperner-s-theorem] The chain has *r* + 1 members and **length** *r*.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/sperner-s-theorem] An *r***-chain-free family** (also called an *r***-family**) is a family of subsets of *E* that contains no chain of length *r*.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/sperner-s-theorem] Erdős (1945) proved that the largest size of an *r*-chain-free family is the sum of the *r* largest binomial coefficients ${\binom {n}{i}}$ .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/sperner-s-theorem] Meshalkin (1963) proved that the maximum size of an antichain of *p*-compositions is the largest *p*-multinomial coefficient ${\binom {n}{n_{1}\ n_{2}\ \dots \ n_{p}}},$ that is, the coefficient in which all *n**i* are as nearly equal as possible (i.e., they differ by at most 1).
[src:extremal-combinatorics/sperner-s-theorem] Meshalkin proved this by proving a generalized LYM inequality.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/sperner-s-theorem] The case *p* = 2 is Sperner's theorem, because then $S_{2}=E\setminus S_{1}$ and the assumptions reduce to the sets $S_{1}$ being a Sperner family.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/sperner-s-theorem] Beck & Zaslavsky (2002) combined the Erdös and Meshalkin theorems by adapting Meshalkin's proof of his generalized LYM inequality.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/sperner-s-theorem] In the finite projective geometry PG(*d*, *F**q*) of dimension *d* over a finite field of order *q*, let ${\mathcal {L}}(p,F_{q})$ be the family of all subspaces.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/sperner-s-theorem] When partially ordered by set inclusion, this family is a lattice.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/sperner-s-theorem] Rota & Harper (1971) proved that the largest size of an antichain in ${\mathcal {L}}(p,F_{q})$ is the largest Gaussian coefficient ${\begin{bmatrix}d+1\\k\end{bmatrix}};$ this is the projective-geometry analog, or *q***-analog**, of Sperner's theorem.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/sperner-s-theorem] They further proved that the largest size of an *r*-chain-free family in ${\mathcal {L}}(p,F_{q})$ is the sum of the *r* largest Gaussian coefficients.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/sperner-s-theorem] Their proof is by a projective analog of the LYM inequality.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/sperner-s-theorem] Beck & Zaslavsky (2003) obtained a Meshalkin-like generalization of the Rota–Harper theorem.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/sperner-s-theorem] In PG(*d*, *F**q*), a **Meshalkin sequence** of length *p* is a sequence $(A_{1},\ldots ,A_{p})$ of projective subspaces such that no proper subspace of PG(*d*, *F**q*) contains them all and their dimensions sum to $d-p+1$ .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] In graph theory, **Turán's theorem** bounds the number of edges that can be included in an undirected graph that does not have a complete subgraph of a given size.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] It is one of the central results of extremal graph theory, an area studying the largest or smallest graphs with given properties, and is a special case of the forbidden subgraph problem on the maximum number of edges in a graph that does not have a given subgraph.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] An example of an n -vertex graph that does not contain any $(r+1)$ -vertex clique $K_{r+1}$ may be formed by partitioning the set of n vertices into r parts of equal or nearly equal size, and connecting two vertices by an edge whenever they belong to two different parts.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] The resulting graph is the Turán graph $T(n,r)$ .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] Turán's theorem states that the Turán graph has the largest number of edges among all *K**r*+1-free n-vertex graphs.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] Turán's theorem, and the Turán graphs giving its extreme case, were first described and studied by Hungarian mathematician Pál Turán in 1941.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] The special case of the theorem for triangle-free graphs is known as **Mantel's theorem**; it was stated in 1907 by Willem Mantel, a Dutch mathematician.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] Turán's theorem states that every graph G with n vertices that does not contain $K_{r+1}$ as a subgraph has at most as many edges as the Turán graph $T(n,r)$ .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] Intuitively, this means that as n gets larger, the fraction of edges included in $T(n,r)$ gets closer and closer to $1-{\frac {1}{r}}$ .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] Many of the following proofs only give the upper bound of $\left(1-{\frac {1}{r}}\right){\frac {n^{2}}{2}}$ .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] Aigner & Ziegler (2018) list five different proofs of Turán's theorem.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] Many of the proofs involve reducing to the case where the graph is a complete multipartite graph, and showing that the number of edges is maximized when there are r parts of size as close as possible to equal.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] Take a $K_{r+1}$ -free graph on n vertices with the maximal number of edges.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] Find a $K_{r}$ (which exists by maximality), and partition the vertices into the set A of the r vertices in the $K_{r}$ and the set B of the $n-r$ other vertices.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] Consider the set A of vertices not adjacent to v and the set B of vertices adjacent to v .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] Now, delete all edges within A and draw all edges between A and B .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] This increases the number of edges by our maximality assumption and keeps the graph $K_{r+1}$ -free.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] Now, B is $K_{r}$ -free, so the same argument can be repeated on B .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] Repeating this argument eventually produces a graph in the same form as a Turán graph, which is a collection of independent sets, with edges between each two vertices from different independent sets.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] A simple calculation shows that the number of edges of this graph is maximized when all independent set sizes are as close to equal as possible.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] This proof, as well as the Zykov Symmetrization proof, involve reducing to the case where the graph is a complete multipartite graph, and showing that the number of edges is maximized when there are r independent sets of size as close as possible to equal.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] Let $S_{1},S_{2},\ldots ,S_{r}$ be the independent sets of the multipartite graph.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] where the left hand side follows from direct counting, and the right hand side follows from complementary counting.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] To show the $\left(1-{\frac {1}{r}}\right){\frac {n^{2}}{2}}$ bound, applying the Cauchy–Schwarz inequality to the ${\textstyle \sum \limits _{i}\left|S_{i}\right|^{2}}$ term on the right hand side suffices, since ${\textstyle \sum \limits _{i}\left|S_{i}\right|=n}$ .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] To prove the Turán Graph is optimal, one can argue that no two $S_{i}$ differ by more than one in size.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] In particular, supposing that we have $\left|S_{i}\right|\geq \left|S_{j}\right|+2$ for some $i\neq j$ , moving one vertex from $S_{i}$ to $S_{j}$ (and adjusting edges accordingly) would increase the value of the sum.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] This can be seen by examining the changes to either side of the above expression for the number of edges, or by noting that the degree of the moved vertex increases.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] This proof is due to Motzkin & Straus (1965).
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] They begin by considering a $K_{r+1}$ free graph with vertices labelled $1,2,\ldots ,n$ , and considering maximizing the function $f(x_{1},x_{2},\ldots ,x_{n})=\sum _{i,j\ {\text{adjacent}}}x_{i}x_{j}$ over all nonnegative $x_{1},x_{2},\ldots ,x_{n}$ with sum 1 .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] This function is known as the Lagrangian of the graph and its edges.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] The idea behind their proof is that if $x_{i},x_{j}$ are both nonzero while $i,j$ are not adjacent in the graph, the function $f(x_{1},\ldots ,x_{i}-t,\ldots ,x_{j}+t,\ldots ,x_{n})$ is linear in t .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] Hence, one can either replace $(x_{i},x_{j})$ with either $(x_{i}+x_{j},0)$ or $(0,x_{i}+x_{j})$ without decreasing the value of the function.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] Hence, there is a point with at most r nonzero variables where the function is maximized.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] Now, the Cauchy–Schwarz inequality gives that the maximal value is at most ${\frac {1}{2}}\left(1-{\frac {1}{r}}\right)$ .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] Plugging in $x_{i}={\frac {1}{n}}$ for all i gives that the maximal value is at least ${\frac {|E|}{n^{2}}}$ , giving the desired bound.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] The key claim in this proof was independently found by Caro and Wei.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] This proof is due to Noga Alon and Joel Spencer, from their book *The Probabilistic Method*.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] A vertex of degree d is included in this with probability ${\frac {1}{d+1}}$ , so this process gives an average of S vertices in the chosen set.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] Applying this fact to the complement graph and bounding the size of the chosen set using the Cauchy–Schwarz inequality proves Turán's theorem.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] See Method of conditional probabilities § Turán's theorem for more.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] Aigner and Ziegler call the final one of their five proofs "the most beautiful of them all".
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] Its origins are unclear, but the approach is often referred to as Zykov Symmetrization as it was used in Zykov's proof of a generalization of Turán's Theorem .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] This proof goes by taking a $K_{r+1}$ -free graph, and applying steps to make it more similar to the Turán Graph while increasing edge count.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] All of these steps keep the graph $K_{r+1}$ free while increasing the number of edges.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] Now, non-adjacency forms an equivalence relation.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] The equivalence classes give that any maximal graph the same form as a Turán graph.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] As in the maximal degree vertex proof, a simple calculation shows that the number of edges is maximized when all independent set sizes are as close to equal as possible.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] The special case of Turán's theorem for $r=2$ is Mantel's theorem: The maximum number of edges in an n -vertex triangle-free graph is $\lfloor n^{2}/4\rfloor .$ In other words, one must delete slightly over half of the edges in $K_{n}$ to obtain a triangle-free graph.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] Another strengthening of Mantel's theorem states that the edges of every n -vertex graph may be covered by at most $\lfloor n^{2}/4\rfloor$ cliques which are either edges or triangles.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] As a corollary, the graph's intersection number (the minimum number of cliques needed to cover all its edges) is at most $\lfloor n^{2}/4\rfloor$ .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] There is no analogous of Turán's theorem for k -uniform hypergraphs.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] In fact, in Turán's original paper, he asked for the maximum number of hyperedges an n -vertex 3 -uniform hypergraph can have without containing the complete 3 -uniform hypergraph on 4 vertices, $K_{4}^{(3)}$ .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] This maximum number of hyperedges is known as the *extremal number*.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] More precisely and more generally, for a hypergraph F , the extremal number of F for n vertices, ex $(n,F)$ , is the maximum number of hyperedges an n -vertex k -uniform hypergraph can have without containing a copy of F .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] To obtain a cleaner parameter, the Turán density of F is defined by the following limit $\pi (F)=\lim _{n\to \infty }{\frac {{\text{ex}}(n,F)}{\binom {n}{k}}}.$ It is easy to see that ${\text{ex}}(n,F)/{\tbinom {n}{k}}$ is non increasing sequence, and therefore, the limit above always converges.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] In this language, an (approximate) answer to Turán's question above, about $K_{4}^{(3)}$ , corresponds to determining the Turán density $\pi (K_{4}^{(3)})$ .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] An upper bound for this can be obtained from the probabilistic method or supersaturation, while a lower bound is given by the complement of the disjoint union of $\lfloor (t-1)/(k-1)\rfloor$ cliques.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] One can see that the Turán graph $T(n,\chi (H)-1)$ cannot contain any copies of H , so the Turán graph establishes the lower bound.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] As a $K_{r+1}$ has chromatic number $r+1$ , Turán's theorem is the special case in which H is a $K_{r+1}$ .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] The general question of how many edges can be included in a graph without a copy of some H is the forbidden subgraph problem.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] Another natural extension of Turán's theorem is the following question: if a graph has no $K_{r+1}$ s, how many copies of $K_{a}$ can it have?
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] Turán's theorem is the case where $a=2$ .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] This was first shown by Zykov (1949) using Zykov Symmetrization.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] Since the Turán Graph contains r parts with size around ${\frac {n}{r}}$ , the number of $K_{a}$ s in $T(n,r)$ is around ${\binom {r}{a}}\left({\frac {n}{r}}\right)^{a}$ .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] As in Erdős–Stone, the Turán graph $T(n,\chi (H)-1)$ attains the desired number of copies of $K_{a}$ .
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] Turan's theorem states that if a graph has edge homomorphism density strictly above $1-{\frac {1}{r-1}}$ , it has a nonzero number of $K_{r}$ s.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] One could ask the far more general question: if you are given the edge density of a graph, what can you say about the density of $K_{r}$ s?
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] An issue with answering this question is that for a given density, there may be some bound not attained by any graph, but approached by some infinite sequence of graphs.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] To deal with this, weighted graphs or graphons are often considered.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] In particular, graphons contain the limit of any infinite sequence of graphs.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] For $d\leq 1-{\frac {1}{r-1}}$ , this gives a graph that is $(r-1)$ -partite and hence gives no $K_{r}$ s.
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] The lower bound was proven by Razborov (2008) for the case of triangles, and was later generalized to all cliques by Reiher (2016).
[src:extremal-combinatorics/turán-s-theorem] The upper bound is a consequence of the Kruskal–Katona theorem .
